WEBVTT

00:06.247 --> 00:09.319
[ Wolf howling,
animals calling ]

00:15.256 --> 00:17.086
♪♪

00:17.120 --> 00:19.053
This season,
in the mountains...

00:19.088 --> 00:21.469
[ Growls ]

00:21.504 --> 00:25.611
Morgan: There's a lot of risk
and uncertainty living out here,

00:25.646 --> 00:27.682
but I don't think anyone
could ever convince me

00:27.717 --> 00:31.169
to live life back in a city.

00:31.203 --> 00:33.895
There's no going back.

00:33.930 --> 00:37.485
Eustace:
I absolutely cherish my freedom,

00:37.520 --> 00:40.661
the freedom to live naturally.

00:40.695 --> 00:43.664
But I'll tell you, friends,
it's not really free.

00:43.698 --> 00:46.943
You go to work for it.

00:46.977 --> 00:50.809
Marty: When you're out there
in the bush, you got to adapt.

00:50.843 --> 00:52.569
I have to make money.

00:52.604 --> 00:55.572
I don't know if I can continue
in the Revelations.

00:55.607 --> 00:58.782
Got a tough decision
I need to make.

00:58.817 --> 01:03.166
Rich: Living wild and free, I
wouldn't have it any other way.

01:03.201 --> 01:04.236
[ Yowls ]

01:04.271 --> 01:06.618
This season, the game population

01:06.652 --> 01:08.240
has really exploded.

01:08.275 --> 01:11.347
It's a never-ending battle,
but it's the only battle I know.

01:11.381 --> 01:13.935
Hey!

01:13.970 --> 01:16.524
Tom: It's not an easy life.

01:16.559 --> 01:20.597
The last two years
haven't been the very best.

01:20.632 --> 01:23.773
I'm determined to make it.

01:23.807 --> 01:28.018
Because living here
in the Yaak is freedom to me.

01:28.053 --> 01:33.265
♪♪

01:33.265 --> 01:38.063
♪♪

01:55.218 --> 01:59.498
Narrator:
Across America's far north,

01:59.533 --> 02:03.537
the freeze descends
without mercy.

02:03.571 --> 02:05.539
In late November,
with the official start

02:05.573 --> 02:07.644
of winter just weeks away,

02:07.679 --> 02:12.339
the temperature
is nearly 50 below zero,

02:12.373 --> 02:17.689
cold so brutal it can cause
frostbite in under 5 minutes,

02:17.723 --> 02:20.174
conditions extreme enough
to rattle

02:20.209 --> 02:22.383
even the most veteran Alaskan.

02:22.418 --> 02:26.525
Marty:
Once it hits 40, 45 below,

02:26.560 --> 02:29.942
it's kind of dangerous
to do anything.

02:29.977 --> 02:32.428
Narrator: But deep freeze
or not, Marty Meierotto

02:32.462 --> 02:35.500
is starting his season today.

02:35.534 --> 02:39.297
Going to try and head out today,
cover some ground.

02:39.331 --> 02:43.370
But it don't get a whole lot
colder than this,

02:43.404 --> 02:45.475
almost 45 below.

02:45.510 --> 02:46.580
But first things first,

02:46.614 --> 02:48.375
I've got to see if this
is going to start

02:48.409 --> 02:50.929
because it is cold.

02:55.105 --> 02:57.453
After 3 years building
a profitable operation

02:57.487 --> 02:59.800
in the remote
Revelation Mountains,

02:59.834 --> 03:05.115
Marty's back to square one
and back on his original line.

03:05.150 --> 03:07.152
The fur market is kind of
like the stock market.

03:07.187 --> 03:08.740
It goes up and down.

03:08.774 --> 03:11.708
Marten aren't paying off,

03:11.743 --> 03:14.332
but lynx are worth
a lot of money.

03:14.366 --> 03:18.439
So I'm going to head back
to my old trap line.

03:18.474 --> 03:21.787
I just need to get out there
and start running some traps

03:21.822 --> 03:23.479
and hopefully catch some fur.

03:23.513 --> 03:26.965
Narrator: Slumping demand from
top fur buyers Russia and China

03:26.999 --> 03:31.383
has driven down the price
of marten to just $5 a pelt.

03:31.418 --> 03:36.664
But a single lynx fur can
still bring more than $500.

03:36.699 --> 03:38.977
Marty's returned here
with a new strategy

03:39.011 --> 03:41.151
to maximize his take
for the season,

03:41.186 --> 03:44.258
but it's a risky proposition.

03:44.293 --> 03:46.398
Lynx are notoriously elusive,

03:46.433 --> 03:51.127
making them hard to find
and harder to trap.

03:51.161 --> 03:53.163
Marty:
It's pretty tough to catch lynx.

03:53.198 --> 03:55.925
They cover a lot of ground.

03:55.959 --> 03:59.411
Narrator: And the deep freeze
is a dangerous complication.

03:59.446 --> 04:03.622
Marty: Metal gets real brittle
when it's this cold.

04:03.657 --> 04:06.660
And I got to stay warm, too.

04:06.694 --> 04:10.111
Just got to take it
a step at a time,

04:10.146 --> 04:13.253
see how far I can make it.

04:13.287 --> 04:15.496
Lynx are a real
specialized predator.

04:15.531 --> 04:20.812
Their almost exclusive prey
is snowshoe hares.

04:20.846 --> 04:22.607
Rabbits are usually
in the lowlands,

04:22.641 --> 04:25.748
brushy or
river-bottom-type stuff.

04:25.782 --> 04:28.647
And farther north,
up by Hard Luck Creek,

04:28.682 --> 04:31.132
I'm hoping that's
better cat country.

04:31.167 --> 04:33.031
So I'll head down there
with the machine

04:33.065 --> 04:35.275
and go see if there
are cats up there

04:35.309 --> 04:39.209
and make some sets.

04:39.244 --> 04:42.316
When things change,
you just have to adapt.

04:42.351 --> 04:44.145
There's no other choice.

04:50.359 --> 04:54.363
I'm breaking new trail,
new country.

04:54.397 --> 04:56.710
And I only got a little
bit of daylight.

04:56.744 --> 05:01.301
But, the problem is
how cold it is outside.

05:04.165 --> 05:05.581
Narrator: 12 miles out,

05:05.615 --> 05:08.894
the temperature drops
to 50 below zero,

05:08.929 --> 05:11.587
so cold that a human
can die from exposure

05:11.621 --> 05:13.796
in under 20 minutes.

05:13.830 --> 05:15.970
♪♪

05:18.628 --> 05:19.284
[ Loud snap ]

05:19.319 --> 05:20.596
Oh!

05:27.223 --> 05:29.398
I snapped a tie-rod.

05:29.432 --> 05:32.159
The ski is just
twisted all around.

05:35.852 --> 05:38.096
It's a bad deal.

05:38.130 --> 05:40.788
On the end of the tie-rod,
there's a linkage

05:40.823 --> 05:44.896
that steers the ski
through the handlebars.

05:44.930 --> 05:48.313
As you can see,
that snapped right off.

05:48.348 --> 05:51.730
Man!

05:51.765 --> 05:54.146
I'm dead in the water
right now.

05:54.181 --> 05:57.287
♪♪

06:07.401 --> 06:10.024
Across the state
and slicing between

06:10.059 --> 06:12.993
the Great Alaska Range
and the Kuskokwim Mountains

06:13.027 --> 06:16.479
is a valley of stony ground
and scrub forest.

06:16.514 --> 06:19.482
Rugged, remote,
and hostile to life,

06:19.517 --> 06:22.934
the area was home to no man

06:22.968 --> 06:26.247
until a single homesteader
staked his claim here.

06:26.282 --> 06:27.628
It's a different way
of life, you know?

06:27.663 --> 06:29.147
It's mostly frozen.

06:29.181 --> 06:33.254
You're mostly on snow or in snow
for 6 months out of the year.

06:33.289 --> 06:35.291
Narrator: Morgan Beasley
narrowly survived

06:35.325 --> 06:36.982
his first winter
in these mountains,

06:37.017 --> 06:40.814
fueled by determination
and simple hard work.

06:40.848 --> 06:44.058
Morgan: So far I've been
able to make a go here,

06:44.093 --> 06:46.785
but I'm going to have
to really step it up

06:46.820 --> 06:48.408
and improve my efficiency.

06:48.442 --> 06:50.858
And I've got a lot of stuff to
build and a lot of stuff to do

06:50.893 --> 06:53.861
before I can really be
the fully functioning homestead

06:53.896 --> 06:56.795
and farm that I imagine.

06:56.830 --> 07:01.904
Fortunately, Morgan is
no longer on his own.

07:01.938 --> 07:02.939
Bunnies outside?

07:02.974 --> 07:04.596
Oh, sure. Yeah,
you can hang them up

07:04.631 --> 07:06.495
in the barn there on a nail.
-Yeah.

07:06.529 --> 07:08.324
Narrator:
Last spring, Margaret Stern,

07:08.358 --> 07:12.293
an experienced horsewoman
and Morgan's long-time friend,

07:12.328 --> 07:14.917
came to care for
his pregnant mares.

07:14.951 --> 07:17.402
And though the horses
failed to give birth,

07:17.437 --> 07:19.646
Margaret chose to stay on.

07:19.680 --> 07:21.786
Margaret: I knew I had a love of
the outdoors from a young age,

07:21.820 --> 07:23.443
and so I have been thinking
about how I would

07:23.477 --> 07:25.755
do certain things
in a wilderness setting

07:25.790 --> 07:27.377
and a homestead situation

07:27.412 --> 07:29.276
because I knew that it was
something that I wanted to do.

07:29.310 --> 07:31.485
And to have somebody
that actually wants to do

07:31.520 --> 07:35.006
all that stuff, too, that's
a pretty remarkable thing.

07:35.040 --> 07:36.594
Morgan: Margaret and I share

07:36.628 --> 07:39.735
a really similar vision
for the future.

07:39.769 --> 07:41.978
She prides herself
on her work ethic.

07:42.013 --> 07:43.911
And I can tell you
that there wouldn't be

07:43.946 --> 07:45.534
near as much stuff
done around here

07:45.568 --> 07:48.295
if Margaret hadn't
been here helping.

07:48.329 --> 07:51.712
One person trying to do
all of this is kind of crazy.

07:51.747 --> 07:52.679
Thanks.

07:52.713 --> 07:53.956
Narrator: Together,

07:53.990 --> 07:55.405
Morgan and Margaret
have spent the summer

07:55.440 --> 07:58.857
improving the land
and expanding the garden.

07:58.892 --> 08:01.032
Now they're ready to tackle
a critical improvement

08:01.066 --> 08:03.690
to their cabin.

08:03.724 --> 08:06.416
Moving it off
its temporary support logs

08:06.451 --> 08:11.698
across a 50-foot gap and onto
a permanent foundation.

08:11.732 --> 08:13.665
Morgan: Today,
it's a big day here,

08:13.700 --> 08:15.564
and it's a pretty critical one.

08:15.598 --> 08:18.498
And there's a lot
that can go wrong.

08:18.532 --> 08:20.776
I've never moved
a building this big.

08:20.810 --> 08:24.918
Right now it's up
just on log skids so, you know,

08:24.952 --> 08:28.059
the cold air can just flow
right in underneath the cabin

08:28.093 --> 08:31.614
so it's colder
than a cabin should be.

08:31.649 --> 08:34.928
Narrator: The new foundation
is a 10-by-15-foot wooden frame

08:34.962 --> 08:38.448
reinforced with concrete
and packed with sand

08:38.483 --> 08:40.968
that will insulate the structure
against cold winds

08:41.003 --> 08:44.903
and ground temperatures,
if Morgan can pull it off.

08:44.938 --> 08:47.630
Morgan: I'll feel a lot better
and feel a lot more safe

08:47.665 --> 08:49.701
if we can get this cabin
onto this foundation

08:49.736 --> 08:52.048
and get it sealed
against the bitter cold

08:52.083 --> 08:55.569
that I know is coming.

08:55.604 --> 08:57.571
Narrator: The plan is to roll
the cabin over the logs

08:57.606 --> 09:01.610
it's currently resting
on using a series of winches.

09:01.644 --> 09:06.511
But first, Morgan must
securely anchor each one.

09:06.546 --> 09:08.168
Morgan: Has to be pretty strong,

09:08.202 --> 09:11.378
because those come-alongs can
develop a couple tons of force.

09:11.412 --> 09:15.589
I want it to move the house, not
rip the stump out of the ground.

09:15.624 --> 09:16.866
Narrator: On the other side,

09:16.901 --> 09:19.213
chains grip the runners
beneath the cabin

09:19.248 --> 09:21.491
and are attached
to come-along winches

09:21.526 --> 09:24.667
that will nudge the cabin
across the 50-foot gap.

09:29.948 --> 09:31.950
Trying to get these
tensioned up.

09:31.985 --> 09:34.159
And this is a really
kind of dangerous time

09:34.194 --> 09:35.609
because we really want it
to move,

09:35.644 --> 09:39.130
so we'll be tempted
to just keep reefing on these.

09:39.164 --> 09:40.683
Margaret:
Little bits at a time?

09:40.718 --> 09:42.478
Yeah, but we don't want
to get too excited

09:42.512 --> 09:44.825
and just keep tensioning
until something breaks.

09:44.860 --> 09:47.759
We want to, you know, go slow,
especially at this point,

09:47.794 --> 09:50.486
until we have a good feel
for everything.

09:50.520 --> 09:53.800
I'm a little bit skeptical
about the cabin moving.

09:53.834 --> 09:56.112
It's kind of one of those things
I'm chalking up to trust

09:56.147 --> 09:59.012
and hoping everything
goes as planned.

09:59.046 --> 10:04.914
[ Winches ratcheting ]

10:04.949 --> 10:06.467
Hold up.

10:06.502 --> 10:08.538
It doesn't seem
to want to budge.

10:08.573 --> 10:11.058
I was worried about that.

10:15.684 --> 10:17.651
♪♪

10:17.686 --> 10:19.653
[ Wind whistling ]

10:19.688 --> 10:24.796
Narrator: It's a bone-chilling
50 degrees below zero in Alaska,

10:24.831 --> 10:28.041
the most extreme conditions
that Marty has ever endured

10:28.075 --> 10:29.490
in the mountains.

10:29.525 --> 10:33.218
And he's just been thrust
into a worst-case scenario.

10:34.841 --> 10:38.741
Marty: The first thing I'm going
to do is get a fire going.

10:38.776 --> 10:41.606
I want to tear into that machine
as quick as I can.

10:41.641 --> 10:47.232
I want to at least have some
light by the time I get it done.

10:47.267 --> 10:50.166
Narrator: The severe cold
snapped the steering mechanism

10:50.201 --> 10:52.134
on his snowmobile.

10:52.168 --> 10:55.344
The machine runs,
but it doesn't steer.

10:55.378 --> 10:56.966
Marty: Even on a nice day,

10:57.001 --> 11:00.763
having my machine break down
is definitely a bummer.

11:00.798 --> 11:05.457
But if it's 50 below,
that's dangerous cold,

11:05.492 --> 11:08.081
and that's going to be
a whole nother ball of wax

11:08.115 --> 11:09.979
I've got to deal with.

11:10.014 --> 11:14.708
Narrator: At these temperatures,
it's deadly to camp overnight.

11:14.743 --> 11:17.090
Marty:
I've got a decent fire here,

11:17.124 --> 11:19.748
so hopefully it will be enough

11:19.782 --> 11:22.164
for me to get the repair done.

11:22.198 --> 11:23.959
♪♪

11:23.993 --> 11:27.100
Narrator: If he can't get
the machine fixed before dark,

11:27.134 --> 11:28.757
he'll have no choice
but to attempt

11:28.791 --> 11:32.036
the 12-mile trek
back to his cabin,

11:32.070 --> 11:34.728
a hike that could leave him
exposed to the elements

11:34.763 --> 11:36.903
for more than five hours.

11:39.664 --> 11:41.114
Marty: Hope it's in here.

11:41.148 --> 11:44.634
You try to carry everything
you think you're going to need.

11:44.669 --> 11:46.947
Invariably, you don't
have it sometimes.

11:54.783 --> 11:57.199
Oh, good. Okay.
Here we go.

11:57.233 --> 12:00.064
That's what broke, right there.

12:00.098 --> 12:02.860
That broke off right there.

12:02.894 --> 12:05.345
So I need to pull that apart

12:05.379 --> 12:08.624
and put this in
without freezing.

12:08.658 --> 12:11.454
It's really cold,

12:11.489 --> 12:15.044
really, really cold.

12:15.079 --> 12:18.634
All right.
So I've got the bolt exposed.

12:19.773 --> 12:22.293
So I've got to take
this shock tower off.

12:32.406 --> 12:35.375
Okay, so I've got
the shock tower off.

12:39.034 --> 12:42.934
Man, it's not moving at all.

12:47.387 --> 12:50.010
Narrator: The spring under the
shock tower will not release,

12:50.045 --> 12:54.532
preventing Marty
from reaching the broken part.

12:54.566 --> 12:56.948
It's been 20 minutes
since the breakdown.

13:02.851 --> 13:05.888
Marty:
I need to get out of here,

13:05.923 --> 13:08.753
and that's all
I'm thinking about.

13:08.788 --> 13:11.273
♪♪

13:20.834 --> 13:22.698
Narrator:
In the Great Alaska Range,

13:22.732 --> 13:25.252
Morgan's rigged a system
of cables and winches

13:25.287 --> 13:30.257
to move his 1,500-foot cabin
onto its new foundation.

13:30.292 --> 13:34.779
But so far, the structure
hasn't budged an inch.

13:34.814 --> 13:36.746
Morgan: I'm going to see
if we can put a big lever

13:36.781 --> 13:38.507
underneath of it
and try to rock the house

13:38.541 --> 13:40.854
and hopefully kind of
break it loose.

13:42.960 --> 13:45.031
Narrator: The cabin is settled
on the original raft

13:45.065 --> 13:48.034
of runner logs that are now
preventing it from shifting.

13:49.863 --> 13:54.661
[ Groans ] Damn it!
It won't budge.

13:54.695 --> 13:55.869
Margaret:
They're frozen.

13:55.904 --> 13:58.147
I've got to break
that friction bond.

14:01.357 --> 14:04.050
Oh, you can see it
breaking free. Nice.

14:04.084 --> 14:05.879
Yep! It just moved.
All right. Well,

14:05.914 --> 14:09.607
let's go crank on them
some more, see what happens.

14:09.641 --> 14:10.297
So...

14:10.332 --> 14:11.264
Ready?

14:11.298 --> 14:15.026
...give yours
a few cranks there.

14:15.061 --> 14:15.889
Oh, it just moved!

14:15.924 --> 14:17.442
Oh, that's too cool!

14:17.477 --> 14:19.306
Yeah.

14:19.341 --> 14:20.273
All right.
Ready?

14:20.307 --> 14:21.861
Hey, we've got it
broke free.

14:21.895 --> 14:23.069
That's a good milestone.

14:23.103 --> 14:26.279
That first little inch when
the roller started to move

14:26.313 --> 14:28.764
and seeing the plan
really working,

14:28.798 --> 14:31.387
that was a very
exciting moment.

14:31.422 --> 14:33.010
Slow and steady.

14:33.044 --> 14:35.322
Now we're just going
to keep cranking it slowly.

14:35.357 --> 14:36.841
Look at it go!

14:36.876 --> 14:38.291
Yeah, that's great.

14:38.325 --> 14:39.740
It's getting it
to roll up closer

14:39.775 --> 14:42.433
until the floor skids
and chains

14:42.467 --> 14:44.814
are right up against
the foundation.

14:44.849 --> 14:47.127
Narrator: They work
slowly and carefully

14:47.162 --> 14:48.542
to keep the cabin level.

14:48.577 --> 14:51.718
Any sudden movement could
cause permanent damage.

14:51.752 --> 14:54.065
Ooh, there was a big one.

14:54.100 --> 14:55.549
Now if this thing
comes apart on us,

14:55.584 --> 14:57.034
we're going to be out cold.

14:57.068 --> 14:59.795
So we really need
to get this done.

15:03.385 --> 15:04.144
Okay, stop!

15:04.179 --> 15:05.042
Okay. And I'm out.

15:05.076 --> 15:06.146
It's done.

15:06.181 --> 15:08.286
Right there,
that's as far we want it.

15:08.321 --> 15:11.393
With the cabin teetering at
the edge of the new foundation,

15:11.427 --> 15:15.500
the next step is to slide it
over the top.

15:15.535 --> 15:19.090
Now let's re-rig and get ready
for the next phase.

15:19.125 --> 15:21.955
Morgan: We're almost ready
to break the house free,

15:21.990 --> 15:23.198
but, right now,

15:23.232 --> 15:26.649
the floor is screwed down
to the skid logs.

15:26.684 --> 15:30.274
So I've got to cut the screws
that are holding this logwork

15:30.308 --> 15:31.585
down onto the floor,

15:31.620 --> 15:34.174
so they can slide it
onto the foundation.

15:34.209 --> 15:36.590
This is going to get
pretty complex.

15:36.625 --> 15:38.109
There's a lot that could happen.

15:38.144 --> 15:39.973
You just got to be ready
to get out of the way.

15:40.008 --> 15:43.011
♪♪

15:51.674 --> 15:55.092
Narrator: Down in the lower 48,

15:55.126 --> 15:58.302
a severe Arctic storm
blowing across Montana

15:58.336 --> 16:02.616
brings heavy snow
and subzero temperatures,

16:02.651 --> 16:05.136
a harsh beginning
to Tom and Nancy Oar's

16:05.171 --> 16:08.553
39th winter in the Yaak Valley.

16:08.588 --> 16:09.796
Nancy: Here you go.

16:09.830 --> 16:11.936
Tom: All right.
Thank you, baby.

16:11.971 --> 16:14.939
The start of the trapping season
has always been a welcome event

16:14.974 --> 16:18.701
for Tom,
who recently turned 73.

16:18.736 --> 16:22.982
But this year, the task ahead
may be harder than ever before.

16:23.016 --> 16:24.707
Tom: It's a hard life.

16:24.742 --> 16:27.987
It never seems
to get much easier.

16:28.021 --> 16:29.229
We're not making
very much money.

16:29.264 --> 16:31.266
In fact, we're losing money.

16:31.300 --> 16:33.233
Narrator: Tom and Nancy
have yet to recover

16:33.268 --> 16:36.202
from two years of losses.

16:36.236 --> 16:39.722
Another unproductive season
could ruin their long-term plans

16:39.757 --> 16:41.655
to remain in the mountains.

16:41.690 --> 16:44.900
Tom: I've kind of decided
that I'm going to take on

16:44.934 --> 16:46.488
an apprentice this year.

16:46.522 --> 16:48.835
And I think I've found
the right person

16:48.869 --> 16:51.700
that could stand in my shoes.

16:51.734 --> 16:53.460
-Hey!
-Hey.

16:53.495 --> 16:54.427
Good morning!

16:54.461 --> 16:56.394
Narrator:
35-year-old Sean McAfee

16:56.429 --> 16:58.362
is a native son of a Yaak

16:58.396 --> 17:00.398
whose family
has been friends of the Oars

17:00.433 --> 17:02.745
since before he was born.

17:02.780 --> 17:05.679
I've known Sean
for a long time now.

17:05.714 --> 17:07.233
I've watched him grow up.

17:07.267 --> 17:08.579
It's chilly out there!

17:08.613 --> 17:11.927
Sean: Tom is truly one of
the quintessential mountain men.

17:11.961 --> 17:14.964
He's one of the last great
trappers and tradesmen.

17:14.999 --> 17:17.829
So to be chosen by Tom
as an apprentice is --

17:17.864 --> 17:18.934
It's a great honor.

17:18.968 --> 17:21.592
Got a day of work
planned out here, I bet?

17:21.626 --> 17:24.560
Yep. I think we're
going to keep busy.

17:24.595 --> 17:27.149
Narrator: Sean's agreed
to lend Tom a hand with labor

17:27.184 --> 17:30.497
in exchange for lessons
in trapping and tanning.

17:30.532 --> 17:33.086
Tom's counting on him
to cover more ground

17:33.121 --> 17:35.054
and boost his output.

17:35.088 --> 17:36.503
Tom: We'll be able
to put out more traps.

17:36.538 --> 17:38.781
We should definitely
catch more fur.

17:38.816 --> 17:42.026
And maybe it'll be better
than it was last year.

17:42.061 --> 17:43.096
Should we get after it?

17:43.131 --> 17:45.616
-Sure! I'll follow.
-Okay. All right.

17:45.650 --> 17:48.964
♪♪

17:48.998 --> 17:50.448
Narrator: Their first
order of business

17:50.483 --> 17:55.108
is setting Tom's 30-mile home
line along the Yaak River.

17:55.143 --> 17:57.283
Have you had these sleds
started since last year, Tom?

17:57.317 --> 17:59.837
No, they ain't been
started in a year.

17:59.871 --> 18:02.840
With this cold weather,
the marten are real active.

18:02.874 --> 18:06.326
So this is the best time
to be trapping.

18:06.361 --> 18:08.570
We've got to get
the snowmobiles going.

18:08.604 --> 18:10.951
[ Engine sputters, starts ]

18:17.026 --> 18:18.235
We got one started!

18:18.269 --> 18:19.753
Old reliable.

18:19.788 --> 18:24.517
Yeah.

18:24.551 --> 18:26.967
Tom: Just got to get
both machines running

18:27.002 --> 18:30.247
and get out there
and set them traps.

18:30.281 --> 18:30.971
Should I prime it once?

18:31.006 --> 18:31.627
Yeah, try it.

18:31.662 --> 18:33.181
Yeah.

18:33.215 --> 18:34.596
Sean: Part of the way of life
of, you know,

18:34.630 --> 18:37.323
living in the Yaak
is starting a snowmobile.

18:37.357 --> 18:39.670
We are a long ways
from the local snowmobile shop.

18:39.704 --> 18:41.879
So it's kind of up to you
to go ahead and fix it.

18:41.913 --> 18:44.123
Want me to pull that
spark plug out there?

18:44.157 --> 18:45.124
Yeah, pull the plugs
out of there.

18:45.158 --> 18:46.159
Put them in
one of those jugs?

18:46.194 --> 18:47.712
Yep.

18:47.747 --> 18:51.233
Put a little fuel down in it,
in this main jug here.

18:51.268 --> 18:52.303
It might fire off.

18:52.338 --> 18:53.166
That'll do her.

18:53.201 --> 18:55.306
I think that'll do her.

19:04.039 --> 19:04.902
Uh-oh.

19:04.936 --> 19:05.868
Oh, no!

19:05.903 --> 19:07.180
Oh boy.

19:07.215 --> 19:09.355
Well, I don't know
what the hell to do now.

19:09.389 --> 19:12.668
♪♪

19:18.571 --> 19:20.711
O0 C1Narrator: It's day one
of the trapping season

19:20.745 --> 19:25.025
in the Yaak Valley, and Tom's
already hit his first snag.

19:25.060 --> 19:28.719
The starting rope pulled out
of this machine.

19:28.753 --> 19:34.242
The options are either
to fix the machine or walk,

19:34.276 --> 19:37.900
so this snowmobile's
really the ticket.

19:37.935 --> 19:39.108
10 millimeter wrench there.

19:39.143 --> 19:41.973
We can start taking
some of these off here.

19:42.008 --> 19:46.530
But Tom's new apprentice
is prepared to step in.

19:46.564 --> 19:48.221
I think if we remove
that whole casing,

19:48.256 --> 19:50.706
we'll be able to get in there
and get that pull cord in

19:50.741 --> 19:51.845
and all hooked back up,

19:51.880 --> 19:53.675
but it's going to take
some wrenching.

19:53.709 --> 19:55.090
You're getting them.

19:55.124 --> 19:58.611
Tom: One thing about Sean,
he's got some mechanic skills.

19:58.645 --> 20:01.338
I have absolutely none.

20:01.372 --> 20:03.995
I'm not a mechanic.
I'm a trapper.

20:04.030 --> 20:07.344
Mechanic? I don't know nothing
about cars and trucks and stuff

20:07.378 --> 20:10.139
and don't want to know
anything about them.

20:10.174 --> 20:12.383
Narrator: Sean reattaches
the same pull cord,

20:12.418 --> 20:15.075
but anchors it more securely.

20:15.110 --> 20:19.252
We just have to tie
that off to the spool.

20:19.287 --> 20:21.599
We want a knot right here,

20:21.634 --> 20:22.600
one that won't break on us

20:22.635 --> 20:24.257
when we're out there
in the woods, huh?

20:24.292 --> 20:25.120
Yeah.

20:25.154 --> 20:29.607
So we go all the way
around.

20:29.642 --> 20:31.230
Think it's twisted enough?

20:31.264 --> 20:32.369
I think so.

20:32.403 --> 20:34.819
It's got spring
on that coil again, right?

20:34.854 --> 20:36.235
Right. Yeah.

20:36.269 --> 20:39.065
Put the top for this guy
back on

20:39.099 --> 20:43.276
and see if it
holds for us.

20:43.311 --> 20:46.417
I'm a little hesitant to go
cranking on that rope

20:46.452 --> 20:47.625
as hard as I did
the first time

20:47.660 --> 20:48.937
because it's
a heartbreaking thing

20:48.971 --> 20:50.835
when a pull rope ends up
in your hand

20:50.870 --> 20:53.424
and doesn't retract
into a snowmobile.

20:53.459 --> 20:55.806
We can go ahead and give her
a shot if you want to, Tom.

20:55.840 --> 20:57.566
All right.

21:00.776 --> 21:02.399
[ Engine sputters ]

21:02.433 --> 21:03.227
Ooh.

21:03.262 --> 21:08.025
[ Engine sputters, starts ]

21:08.059 --> 21:09.820
Whoo!

21:09.854 --> 21:11.891
All right!

21:11.925 --> 21:14.411
♪♪

21:14.445 --> 21:16.551
Tom: It excites me
to have Sean out here.

21:16.585 --> 21:19.450
It looks like he's starting
to prove himself already,

21:19.485 --> 21:22.177
and we haven't even
started trapping yet.

21:26.595 --> 21:28.321
♪♪

21:28.356 --> 21:30.323
[ Yowls ]

21:36.295 --> 21:38.642
Narrator: A near-record
deep freeze is setting in

21:38.676 --> 21:40.885
across the American northwest,

21:40.920 --> 21:42.887
holding Montana in its grip

21:42.922 --> 21:45.373
and sending predators
into a frenzy.

21:45.407 --> 21:46.546
[ Yowls ]

21:48.962 --> 21:53.381
Predators are really
giving me a hard time.

21:53.415 --> 21:55.797
We got a bunch of snow
already, early.

21:55.831 --> 21:57.833
The snow pushes all
of the game down.

21:57.868 --> 21:59.939
They're coming down into
the rancher's fields,

21:59.973 --> 22:02.113
eating hay and stuff
with the cattle,

22:02.148 --> 22:05.324
so the predators are going
to come down lower, too.

22:05.358 --> 22:08.396
Narrator: Rich Lewis stands
watch over the Ruby Valley,

22:08.430 --> 22:13.504
and he's had little rest
since the early winter arrived.

22:13.539 --> 22:16.438
Local ranchers rely on him
to protect their herds

22:16.473 --> 22:18.923
and their families.

22:18.958 --> 22:21.270
And this season,
it's already shaping up

22:21.305 --> 22:23.687
to be a full-time job.

22:23.721 --> 22:25.792
Rich:
I got another call this morning.

22:25.827 --> 22:28.174
Rancher's worried.
He's got, like, 20,000 acres,

22:28.208 --> 22:30.279
and he thinks something's
spooked his cattle.

22:30.314 --> 22:33.662
I'm assuming it's a lion,
so I've got to check it out.

22:36.320 --> 22:38.011
It's a good 25, 30 below,

22:38.046 --> 22:40.531
so I've got to get
Wilbur started.

22:40.566 --> 22:43.154
Narrator: Last winter, Rich
converted his trusty old truck,

22:43.189 --> 22:45.294
Wilbur, into
a mobile command center

22:45.329 --> 22:49.368
where he camps out to stay
one step ahead of predators.

22:49.402 --> 22:50.679
Rich:
Smoke's coming up through now

22:50.714 --> 22:53.820
so I'm starting to get
some heat rising.

22:53.855 --> 22:56.892
I've got Wilbur set up
so I can stay in my camper.

22:56.927 --> 23:01.310
Got food and a wood stove
so, I mean, I can hunker down.

23:01.345 --> 23:03.899
Well, Wilbur, you ready
to rock and roll?

23:07.075 --> 23:10.216
[ Engine starts ]

23:10.250 --> 23:11.597
All right.

23:11.631 --> 23:13.668
Well, I'm going to go
and start looking for tracks.

23:19.812 --> 23:23.609
I'm going to try to check out
the perimeter and see what --

23:23.643 --> 23:25.438
the farther I can get away
from everything,

23:25.473 --> 23:28.648
so I can see what's coming in.

23:28.683 --> 23:31.306
Narrator: Scouting
the entire 75-mile border

23:31.340 --> 23:33.377
of the rancher's land
for signs of an intruder

23:33.412 --> 23:35.517
could take several days.

23:35.552 --> 23:37.692
But if there's a lion
in the area,

23:37.726 --> 23:40.695
the dogs should be able
to pick up the trace.

23:40.729 --> 23:42.041
Rich:
Fences don't look too bad.

23:42.075 --> 23:46.390
They're all -- Nothing's
really tore through them.

23:46.425 --> 23:48.357
Let's see what's
going on up here.

24:00.335 --> 24:02.648
[ Groans ]

24:02.682 --> 24:05.271
Come on, Wilbur.

24:05.305 --> 24:08.067
There's some big tracks there.

24:17.973 --> 24:21.460
Huh.

24:21.494 --> 24:23.462
That's not lion tracks.

24:26.534 --> 24:28.190
It's a damn grizzly bear.

24:28.225 --> 24:30.330
♪♪

24:36.371 --> 24:39.512
O0 C1Narrator:
In Montana's cattle country,

24:39.547 --> 24:42.066
winter is a dangerous time
for livestock

24:42.101 --> 24:45.414
as hungry wolves and cougars
descend from the mountains

24:45.449 --> 24:48.107
in search of easy prey.

24:48.141 --> 24:51.386
But an early cold snap
is disrupting the natural order,

24:51.420 --> 24:55.252
bringing an unexpected threat
to the Ruby Valley.

24:55.286 --> 24:57.288
♪♪

25:00.084 --> 25:03.674
Bears ain't supposed
to be out now.

25:03.709 --> 25:05.607
Ooh, that's not that old.

25:07.644 --> 25:09.542
Holy cow!

25:09.577 --> 25:12.959
It's a good-sized grizzly.

25:12.994 --> 25:14.582
God, he must be hungry.

25:14.616 --> 25:16.618
He came down to the fence.
Looks like he's turned.

25:16.653 --> 25:19.345
He's heading right down
where those cattle are.

25:19.379 --> 25:20.553
Usually this time of year,

25:20.588 --> 25:21.934
we don't have grizzly bears,
you know?

25:21.968 --> 25:23.142
They're hibernating.

25:23.176 --> 25:25.316
I don't know why he got up
from his den,

25:25.351 --> 25:26.904
or he hasn't denned yet.

25:26.939 --> 25:29.666
It's hard to say
what's going on.

25:31.944 --> 25:33.359
Maybe he smelled
the cattle or something.

25:33.393 --> 25:35.534
Bears can't see
very well at all,

25:35.568 --> 25:38.329
but they have
a really good nose.

25:38.364 --> 25:40.021
Narrator:
A grizzly's sense of smell

25:40.055 --> 25:43.956
is 2,000 times more powerful
than a human's.

25:43.990 --> 25:48.823
And a single bear can devour up
to 75 pounds of meat at a time,

25:48.857 --> 25:53.137
making the rancher's cattle
a prime target.

25:53.172 --> 25:56.727
Problem we have is
grizzly bears are endangered.

25:56.762 --> 25:59.488
You can't shoot a grizzly
unless it's self-defense.

25:59.523 --> 26:03.803
So this is going to be
nothing but trouble.

26:03.838 --> 26:05.840
[ Whimpers ]

26:05.874 --> 26:08.187
Narrator: A grizzly on the prowl
so late in the season

26:08.221 --> 26:10.154
is more likely to be aggressive

26:10.189 --> 26:14.262
as it hunts for every last scrap
of food to hibernate for winter.

26:14.296 --> 26:16.609
[ Roars ]

26:16.644 --> 26:18.542
Rich:
We can't run bear with dogs.

26:18.577 --> 26:20.544
My dogs couldn't hold up
against a grizzly.

26:20.579 --> 26:22.132
They're not trained for that,

26:22.166 --> 26:24.824
and I don't want to take
a chance on getting killed.

26:24.859 --> 26:27.378
I'm going to track him out here
because if he's headed down

26:27.413 --> 26:29.760
to the rancher's cattle,
we've got a problem.

26:33.074 --> 26:35.007
♪♪

26:40.357 --> 26:42.359
Narrator:
In the Great Alaska Range,

26:42.393 --> 26:47.398
the final step of the cabin
move is also the riskiest --

26:47.433 --> 26:49.918
sliding it onto
its new foundation.

26:49.953 --> 26:52.645
Come on!
Oh, hey.

26:52.680 --> 26:54.543
Cool.
We're through.

26:54.578 --> 26:56.787
Morgan's prepared the structure
by severing it

26:56.822 --> 26:58.962
from its old floorboards,

26:58.996 --> 27:01.240
but with nothing now
bracing it together,

27:01.274 --> 27:05.209
the danger of collapse
is greater than ever.

27:05.244 --> 27:07.695
Morgan: Now is where things
are most likely to go wrong

27:07.729 --> 27:10.076
because if it kind of slides
off the foundation

27:10.111 --> 27:12.596
or does something weird
or something comes apart,

27:12.631 --> 27:14.425
the whole mess could
come crashing down.

27:14.460 --> 27:16.496
[ Sighs ] Okay.

27:16.531 --> 27:20.017
-Ready?
-Ready?

27:20.052 --> 27:22.986
It could start to go
pretty fast so be...

27:23.020 --> 27:25.471
Okay....be ready to get out of
the way if it comes apart.

27:30.303 --> 27:33.548
-Ooh!
-Here it comes.

27:45.353 --> 27:47.942
I'm on something
tight here.

27:47.976 --> 27:51.324
Mine just kind of stopped
moving a little bit.

27:51.359 --> 27:53.188
Something's wonky.

27:57.641 --> 28:00.713
Oh, man, something's really...
That's not good.

28:00.748 --> 28:02.819
Yeah, I don't know
why it's not moving.

28:05.235 --> 28:08.928
Seriously, what is going
on with this?

28:08.963 --> 28:11.482
It's just --
Oh! It just caught on...

28:11.517 --> 28:13.968
There's a tall
floorboard here.

28:19.456 --> 28:21.078
I need a wedge.
I can just...

28:21.113 --> 28:22.597
Whoa, there it goes!

28:22.631 --> 28:25.945
Whoa! Ohh!

28:25.980 --> 28:27.602
Yeah, it's good now!

28:27.636 --> 28:28.292
All right.

28:28.327 --> 28:29.638
Hold on,

28:29.673 --> 28:32.158
I think my heart
just skipped a beat.

28:32.193 --> 28:37.025
That could've slid.
It could've hit me pretty hard.

28:37.060 --> 28:38.026
[ Sighs, chuckles ]

28:38.061 --> 28:39.718
There's some tension
built up there.

28:39.752 --> 28:41.616
I got a little scared
there for a second.

28:41.650 --> 28:43.583
I thought I was going
to get smacked in the face

28:43.618 --> 28:45.206
with a house.

28:45.240 --> 28:48.657
You know, it's a huge relief
to see that onto the sill,

28:48.692 --> 28:50.383
but we still have
a long ways to go,

28:50.418 --> 28:52.765
and the whole way it's going
to be a little iffy.

28:52.800 --> 28:56.182
We've got to get it
onto this foundation,

28:56.217 --> 28:58.529
and then I can sleep tonight.

29:04.259 --> 29:08.160
Narrator:
One hour from sundown in Alaska,

29:08.194 --> 29:11.957
Marty is stranded 12 miles
from shelter in the deadly cold.

29:14.822 --> 29:18.826
It's minus 50 and falling
as he struggles to replace

29:18.860 --> 29:20.759
a snapped tie-rod.

29:20.793 --> 29:25.798
Extreme conditions are taking
their toll on machine and man.

29:25.833 --> 29:27.420
Man!

29:27.455 --> 29:29.802
♪♪

29:29.837 --> 29:32.218
[ Grunts ] All right.
There we go.

29:38.846 --> 29:41.641
The grease is like tar.

29:44.679 --> 29:48.096
Okay, so there's the piece
that's broken.

29:48.131 --> 29:50.892
And there's the piece I need.

29:50.927 --> 29:55.276
Now you can see this
big arm snapped off

29:55.310 --> 29:58.555
and that's how it steers.

29:58.589 --> 30:01.420
I just got to put it all
back together,

30:01.454 --> 30:04.630
and sometimes
that's the hardest part.

30:04.664 --> 30:06.045
Narrator: Marty has been
out in the open

30:06.080 --> 30:09.290
for more than three hours,
and now,

30:09.324 --> 30:12.880
to speed up the fix,
he must get hands-on.

30:16.642 --> 30:21.474
Marty: If any skin's exposed for
very long, it's going to freeze.

30:21.509 --> 30:23.614
It's not a maybe.

30:23.649 --> 30:27.101
Frostbite is just like
a really bad burn.

30:27.135 --> 30:29.862
It just keeps going,
and pretty soon,

30:29.897 --> 30:32.382
it's eating up your flesh.

30:37.766 --> 30:38.975
There we go.

30:39.009 --> 30:42.150
In theory, I'm fixed!

30:42.185 --> 30:45.602
So I should have steering.

30:45.636 --> 30:48.156
You know, I don't know
if I'm super tight,

30:48.191 --> 30:51.919
but it's tight enough
to get me out of here,

30:51.953 --> 30:55.992
and right now that's
all I really care about.

30:56.026 --> 30:59.202
I had a plan to go
set traps today,

30:59.236 --> 31:02.101
and Mother Nature decided

31:02.136 --> 31:05.553
it was time for me to wrench
on a snow machine at 45 below,

31:05.587 --> 31:08.970
so that's what I got to do.

31:09.005 --> 31:11.007
It's starting to go now.

31:15.666 --> 31:18.221
Being out here,
you're not in control.

31:18.255 --> 31:20.050
If the worst comes,
you've got to deal with it.

31:20.085 --> 31:22.087
There's nothing you can
do about it.

31:22.121 --> 31:25.953
But hopefully it'll be
a better day tomorrow.

31:25.987 --> 31:28.610
♪♪

31:35.307 --> 31:36.618
Narrator: In Montana,

31:36.653 --> 31:38.931
Tom's trapping season
is under way,

31:38.966 --> 31:42.383
and for the first time ever,
he's not alone.

31:44.419 --> 31:46.628
Looking to dig out
of a 2-year slump,

31:46.663 --> 31:48.699
he's decided to bring
on an apprentice

31:48.734 --> 31:52.151
to help turn his luck around.

31:52.186 --> 31:54.843
Tom: There's so much
to learn about trapping

31:54.878 --> 31:58.951
that he'll be with me
a year or two before he knows

31:58.986 --> 32:00.953
very much about it, really.

32:00.988 --> 32:03.404
Narrator: Tom spent four decades
perfecting the work

32:03.438 --> 32:05.130
of trapping and tanning.

32:05.164 --> 32:09.203
This winter will be a master
class for the young outdoorsman,

32:09.237 --> 32:11.826
Sean, who's offered up
his labor in exchange

32:11.860 --> 32:14.380
for a share of Tom's expertise.

32:14.415 --> 32:18.039
Let me show you
how these marten sets go.

32:18.074 --> 32:20.628
With the price of marten
at an all-time low,

32:20.662 --> 32:23.665
Tom uses his tanning skills
to make a profit

32:23.700 --> 32:27.117
by turning raw pelts
into high-value crafts,

32:27.152 --> 32:28.981
so every catch counts.

32:29.016 --> 32:31.673
This bait that I'm using
for the pine marten here

32:31.708 --> 32:34.090
is tainted beaver meat.

32:34.124 --> 32:38.301
It's about a week old,
which pine marten really like.

32:38.335 --> 32:39.371
You put it back
in the bucket?

32:39.405 --> 32:42.995
Yep, way down in there
in the bottom.

32:43.030 --> 32:46.309
The neat thing about these
little mailbox cubbies

32:46.343 --> 32:49.174
is that you can put your bait
way back in the back

32:49.208 --> 32:51.762
and nothing can see it
back there.

32:51.797 --> 32:54.455
Pine marten, they'll smell it
from a distance,

32:54.489 --> 32:56.871
and they'll come into it
and they'll go right at the pole

32:56.905 --> 32:59.391
and into the trap.

33:07.019 --> 33:11.023
This trap sets in the entrance
of the box,

33:11.058 --> 33:15.131
and when the marten steps
on this little pan here,

33:15.165 --> 33:18.030
it will catch the marten
around the head and kill him.

33:18.065 --> 33:21.482
Now, the deerskin
is a scent holder.

33:21.516 --> 33:23.311
You just hang this
underneath the box...

33:23.346 --> 33:26.901
-Okay.
-...like so.

33:26.935 --> 33:31.319
This here, this is
sun-rendered fish oil.

33:31.354 --> 33:33.425
I'm just going to have
to pour it, I guess.

33:33.459 --> 33:35.565
You always use just fish oil
for marten sets?

33:35.599 --> 33:40.604
Sometimes I'll mix skunk essence
into the fish oil.

33:40.639 --> 33:41.640
Okay.

33:41.674 --> 33:42.606
And that gives it...Real pungent.

33:42.641 --> 33:46.610
...a stronger smell.

33:46.645 --> 33:49.406
Sean: That knowledge
of the trapping and the woods,

33:49.441 --> 33:52.616
those are types of things that
could one day just disappear.

33:52.651 --> 33:55.033
And it's something that
I'll hold dear to my heart

33:55.067 --> 33:56.896
just because I'll be able
to do it with my son one day,

33:56.931 --> 33:59.554
and hopefully he can
do it with his.

33:59.589 --> 34:01.108
That burned-hair kind of...

34:01.142 --> 34:03.351
is that putting off
scent itself, too, or...

34:03.386 --> 34:06.389
Mm-hmm. Yeah.
Look at that smoke.

34:06.423 --> 34:09.047
Once they get to
the fish oil scent,

34:09.081 --> 34:10.393
then they'll smell
the beaver.

34:10.427 --> 34:11.152
Okay.

34:11.187 --> 34:11.842
Hopefully.
[ Chuckles ]

34:11.877 --> 34:12.498
Hopefully.

34:12.533 --> 34:13.154
Do another set?

34:13.189 --> 34:13.844
Yep.

34:13.879 --> 34:16.571
All right.

34:16.606 --> 34:19.091
Well,
we're getting them out.

34:22.301 --> 34:23.958
Do you want me
to prep this trap?

34:23.992 --> 34:25.235
Yeah, you can do that.

34:25.270 --> 34:26.581
Okay.

34:26.616 --> 34:28.549
Tom: The thing about Sean
is he's not a trapper at all.

34:28.583 --> 34:30.620
He knows nothing about trapping.

34:30.654 --> 34:34.865
But he's a real woodsman,
and that's really what it takes.

34:36.798 --> 34:41.355
Tom: And just bend your trap
spring up a little bit.

34:43.426 --> 34:45.290
Looks good.

34:45.324 --> 34:49.397
To watch him do the things
that I'm normally doing,

34:49.432 --> 34:52.676
you know, it looks like
he's going to be up to snuff.

34:52.711 --> 34:53.884
It really does.

34:53.919 --> 34:56.611
I'm excited about
having him, you know,

34:56.646 --> 35:00.339
and -- and maybe we'll have
a better trapping season

35:00.374 --> 35:02.583
than what we've have
in the last couple years.

35:02.617 --> 35:03.549
All right, mister.

35:03.584 --> 35:04.550
Yep.

35:04.585 --> 35:07.277
We got a lot more to go.

35:10.315 --> 35:12.248
♪♪

35:14.733 --> 35:17.045
Narrator: 400 miles south,

35:17.080 --> 35:20.428
Rich is tracking
a rogue grizzly.

35:20.463 --> 35:23.017
The giant predator is hungriest

35:23.051 --> 35:25.606
and most dangerous
at this time of year

35:25.640 --> 35:28.712
as it prepares for hibernation.

35:28.747 --> 35:30.818
And all signs
point to it stalking

35:30.852 --> 35:33.372
a rancher's valuable cattle.

35:33.407 --> 35:37.721
Rich: Oh, he's heading right
down to where those cattle are.

35:37.756 --> 35:42.174
These cows are all bunched up
like they're watching something.

35:42.209 --> 35:43.520
This ain't right for these cows

35:43.555 --> 35:46.005
to all be standing here
bunched up.

35:46.040 --> 35:48.836
Something's kind of
got them spooked.

35:50.596 --> 35:54.048
These tracks are fresh.

35:54.082 --> 35:56.809
It's late last night
or early this morning,

35:56.844 --> 35:58.156
and he's a predator.

35:58.190 --> 35:59.191
You don't know
what he's going to do.

35:59.226 --> 36:01.193
He's probably over 500 pounds.

36:01.228 --> 36:04.507
He can do whatever he wants.

36:04.541 --> 36:07.475
He's still headed this way.

36:07.510 --> 36:08.752
I'm just going to try
to track him out,

36:08.787 --> 36:10.547
and hopefully I can get him
pushed off this land

36:10.582 --> 36:13.792
without too much trouble.

36:13.826 --> 36:18.210
Narrator:
Grizzly bears are classified as
endangered species in Montana.

36:18.245 --> 36:20.316
If Rich encounters the beast,

36:20.350 --> 36:23.560
his only protection
will be a warning shot.

36:27.806 --> 36:29.117
You got to be careful
with grizzlies

36:29.152 --> 36:31.879
because they'll double
back and track you.

36:31.913 --> 36:33.743
They're a smart animal.

36:39.921 --> 36:40.991
That's some scat.

36:41.026 --> 36:43.408
It still ain't froze
all the way,

36:43.442 --> 36:48.654
so he's not too far
around here somewhere.

36:48.689 --> 36:50.829
Boy, this grizzly's
got some long claws,

36:50.863 --> 36:53.141
been licking on that salt block.

36:53.176 --> 36:54.764
Narrator:
Ranchers leave salt blocks

36:54.798 --> 36:57.905
scattered around their property
to keep the cattle healthy.

36:57.939 --> 37:02.254
But they're beacons for other
wildlife, including predators.

37:02.289 --> 37:04.291
He was licking on it like crazy.

37:04.325 --> 37:06.603
Bears like to lick on
salt blocks, too, you know?

37:06.638 --> 37:08.295
They need salt.

37:08.329 --> 37:11.090
That bear's got to be right
in front of me here somewhere.

37:18.719 --> 37:21.860
Man, he's got to be close.
I can smell him.

37:21.894 --> 37:23.586
[ Sniffs ]

37:23.620 --> 37:25.450
Something moved up there.

37:25.484 --> 37:27.245
[ Bear grunting ]

37:27.279 --> 37:29.764
There he is. There's the bear.

37:36.288 --> 37:38.359
O0 C1Narrator:
In Montana's Ruby Valley...

37:38.394 --> 37:40.050
Rich:
Get out of here, bear!

37:40.085 --> 37:43.226
...Rich stands his ground.

37:43.261 --> 37:45.746
[ Bear panting ]

37:45.780 --> 37:48.507
[ Bear grunting ]

37:48.542 --> 37:50.198
[ Gunshots ]

37:50.233 --> 37:51.407
Get out of here!

37:51.441 --> 37:54.720
[ Bear panting ]

37:54.755 --> 37:58.586
Narrator: Unable to fire
directly at the bear,

37:58.621 --> 38:01.071
all Rich can do
is sound a warning,

38:01.106 --> 38:04.040
but grizzlies are known
to charge when threatened.

38:05.006 --> 38:06.560
[ Gunshot ]

38:15.500 --> 38:18.330
He's moving off.
He's getting out of here.

38:21.540 --> 38:22.955
Whew, that was close.

38:22.990 --> 38:25.544
I didn't know if I was going
down or not for dinner.

38:30.825 --> 38:34.139
He's heading back up
to the high country.

38:34.173 --> 38:37.901
Well, that scared him
away from the cattle.

38:37.936 --> 38:40.594
Maybe he's going up
to his den to den up.

38:43.390 --> 38:46.324
I was looking down at
the tracks, and I just turned.

38:46.358 --> 38:47.911
Bear looked at me,
and I looked at him.

38:47.946 --> 38:50.604
I mean, my heart stopped there
for a second, you know?

38:50.638 --> 38:52.916
I mean,
that was pretty wild.

38:52.951 --> 38:56.057
♪♪

38:56.092 --> 38:57.438
He ran out of here
pretty good.

38:57.473 --> 39:01.235
Hopefully, I'm pretty sure
he's off the ranch now.

39:01.269 --> 39:05.688
I'm done. I got to get
back to Wilbur now.

39:05.722 --> 39:08.415
The grizzly incursion this late
in the season is a sign

39:08.449 --> 39:11.245
that the predators are out
in force this winter

39:11.279 --> 39:14.731
and that Rich will have
to remain vigilant.

39:14.766 --> 39:16.284
Rich: I haven't been through
the whole ranch yet,

39:16.319 --> 39:18.425
so I just got to keep going.

39:18.459 --> 39:20.254
What do you say, buddy?

39:20.288 --> 39:21.945
Good boy.

39:21.980 --> 39:23.153
You missed a wild one,
Hatchet.

39:23.188 --> 39:26.191
You wouldn't believe
it if I told you.

39:26.225 --> 39:28.089
You guys had her easy today.

39:30.678 --> 39:32.439
Ah, this fire feels good.

39:34.648 --> 39:36.235
Well, I got to get some sleep.

39:36.270 --> 39:38.099
Got a long day ahead
of me tomorrow.

39:41.689 --> 39:43.415
[ Sighs ]

39:43.450 --> 39:46.591
I'm not wore out yet, but it's
going to be a long winter.

39:46.625 --> 39:48.765
♪♪

40:02.434 --> 40:04.574
Narrator:
In the Great Alaska Range,

40:04.609 --> 40:06.438
the cabin move is
nearly complete,

40:06.473 --> 40:09.165
as the winches close
the remaining gap

40:09.199 --> 40:11.098
1 inch at a time.

40:16.759 --> 40:19.037
Morgan:
Let's get this done.

40:19.071 --> 40:20.763
Whoo.

40:20.797 --> 40:24.422
Oh. There it goes.
That's got to be good there.

40:24.456 --> 40:25.906
Let's go look at
the front.

40:25.940 --> 40:27.942
[ Chuckles ]

40:27.977 --> 40:29.496
Oh, my God.

40:29.530 --> 40:30.945
All right!

40:30.980 --> 40:32.050
Look at that.

40:32.084 --> 40:35.743
Such a huge change
in a day.

40:35.778 --> 40:36.917
Morgan: It's quite something.

40:36.951 --> 40:38.746
I can't tell you how cool
it is to see it

40:38.781 --> 40:40.921
and how gratifying it is.

40:40.955 --> 40:42.198
Cool new porch.

40:42.232 --> 40:43.717
Even though the house
is on the foundation,

40:43.751 --> 40:44.718
our work isn't over.

40:44.752 --> 40:46.098
We have to put in a floor.

40:46.133 --> 40:48.204
It's going to be
a whole lot of work.

40:48.238 --> 40:49.964
Wow, beautiful.

40:49.999 --> 40:51.103
See, it's not that bad.

40:51.138 --> 40:52.795
Oh, come on.

40:52.829 --> 40:54.521
I'm not living here
when it's mud floor.

40:54.555 --> 40:55.487
I'm sorry.

40:55.522 --> 40:56.454
No, it's not going
to be mud.

40:56.488 --> 40:57.455
Uh-huh.

40:57.489 --> 40:58.525
Yeah, it's not
going to be mud.

40:58.559 --> 40:59.871
Yeah, it's just
going to be icy.

40:59.905 --> 41:01.355
I have my limits, Beasley.

41:04.910 --> 41:06.394
♪♪

41:06.429 --> 41:09.708
Narrator: This season
on "Mountain Men"...

41:09.743 --> 41:12.366
Morgan: I have to do everything
I can to be prepared.

41:12.400 --> 41:13.540
Oh. Oh.

41:13.574 --> 41:15.507
There's no room for mistakes.

41:20.926 --> 41:22.583
Rich: The mountain lions
are really active.

41:22.618 --> 41:25.966
Holy crap!
There's a cat in the tree!

41:26.000 --> 41:26.829
[ Dogs barking, howling ]

41:26.863 --> 41:28.002
I've got my work cut out for me

41:28.037 --> 41:29.832
if I'm going to
keep this valley safe.

41:31.316 --> 41:34.526
Jason: We've had
some major setbacks.

41:34.561 --> 41:36.321
Mission right now --
looking for a home.

41:36.355 --> 41:37.356
I got him.

41:37.391 --> 41:40.083
It's time to start over.

41:40.118 --> 41:43.362
Tom: With Sean,
there's a million things yet

41:43.397 --> 41:44.743
we need to teach him,

41:44.778 --> 41:47.781
but once he gets that knowledge
into his head,

41:47.815 --> 41:50.128
maybe we'll have
a better trapping season

41:50.162 --> 41:53.372
than what we've had
in the last couple years.

41:53.407 --> 41:56.410
Marty: I'm way behind where
I thought I was going to be.

41:56.444 --> 42:01.449
I have to figure something out,
but if I push it too far,

42:01.484 --> 42:03.486
I'm going to be
in a lot of trouble.

42:03.521 --> 42:06.385
We're in a bad situation.

42:06.420 --> 42:08.318
Eustace: This is really
shaping up to be

42:08.353 --> 42:11.529
one of the hardest winters
I've ever had at Turtle Island.

42:11.563 --> 42:14.670
But we just do what we have
to do to get the job done.

42:14.704 --> 42:16.982
Ooh, that's going fast!

42:17.017 --> 42:19.157
♪♪
